===Etymology 1===
{{etymon|en|id=institution|:der|frm:banque<id:bank>|tree=1}}
[[File:Bank of England Building, London, UK - Diliff.jpg|thumb|The {{w|Bank of England}} is one of the first modern central '''banks''' ({{senseno|en|Q22687}}), established in 1694.]]

From {{inh|en|enm|banke}}, from {{der|en|frm|banque}}, from {{der|en|it|banca||counter, moneychanger's bench or table}}, from {{der|en|lng|bank||bench, counter}}, from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*banki}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*bankiz||bench, counter}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*bÊ°eg-||to turn, curve, bend, bow}}. {{doublet|en|bench|banc|banco}}.

For the bench-bank relation, compare typologically {{m+|ru|Ğ»Ğ°ÌĞ²ĞºĞ°}}, {{m|ru|Ğ¿Ñ€Ğ¸Ğ»Ğ°ÌĞ²Ğ¾Ğº}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{senseid|en|Q22687}} {{lb|en|countable}} An [[institution]] where one can place and borrow [[money]] and take care of [[financial]] affairs.
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-01|volume=407|issue=8838|page=71|magazine=w:The Economist
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21578670-peer-peer-lending-needs-new-name-end-peer-show End of the peer show]
|passage=Finance is seldom romantic. But the idea of peer-to-peer lending comes close. This is an industry that brings together individual savers and lenders on online platforms.{{...}}'''Banks''' and credit-card firms are kept out of the picture. Talk to enough people in the field and someone is bound to mention the â€œdemocratisation of financeâ€.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[branch office]] of such an institution.
#: {{syn|en|Lombard house<q:archaic>}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} An underwriter or [[controller]] of a [[card game]].
#: {{syn|en|banker|banque}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A fund from [[deposits]] or [[contributions]], to be used in transacting [[business]]; a [[joint]] [[stock]] or [[capital]].
#* {{RQ:Bacon Essayes|chapter=Of Usury|passage=Let it be no '''bank''' or common stock, but every man be master of his own money.}}
# {{lb|en|gambling|countable}} The sum of money etc. which the [[dealer]] or [[banker]] has as a [[fund]] from which to draw [[stake]]s and pay [[loss]]es.
# {{lb|en|slang|uncountable}} [[money|Money]]; [[profit]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2010|author=Paul Bouchard|title=Enlistment|page=113|passage=Military dude was working for a drug dealer, right? and making good '''bank''' with itâ€”he was making good money.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} In certain games, such as [[domino]]s, a fund of [[piece]]s from which the players are allowed to draw.
# {{lb|en|countable|mostly|in combination}} A [[safe]] and [[guaranteed]] place of [[storage]] for and [[retrieval]] of important items or goods.
#: {{co|en|[[blood bank|blood '''bank''']]; [[data bank|data '''bank''']]; [[sperm bank|sperm '''bank''']]}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A device used to store coins or currency.
#: {{ux|en|If you want to buy a bicycle, you need to put the money in your piggy '''bank'''.}}

