===Etymology 2===
{{etymon|en|id=river edge}}
[[File:Perfume River Bank, as seen from TrÆ°á»ng Tiá»n Bridge, 2019.jpg|thumb|A river '''bank''' ({{senseno|en|edge}})]]

From {{inh|en|enm|bank}}, {{m|enm|banke}}, from {{inh|en|ang|*banca|t=bench}} (attested in {{cog|ang|hÅbanca|t=couch}} and {{inh|en|ang|banc|t=bank, hillock, embankment}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*bankÅ}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*bankÃ´}}. Akin to {{cog|non|bakki|t=elevation, hill}}, {{cog|no|bakke|t=slope, hill}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# {{senseid|en|edge}} {{lb|en|hydrology}} An [[edge]] of [[river]], [[lake]], or other [[watercourse]].
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Julius Caesar|I|i|passage=Tiber trembled underneath her '''banks'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=June 8, 1943|title=Jap Remnants Suffer Heavy Casualties: Alerts In Chungking
|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.granth.10715/|journal=w:The Bombay Chronicle|volume=XXXI|issue=134|page=1|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/dli.granth.10715/
|text=On the opposite '''bank''' of the river other Chinese units attacked Taoshih and Yunmeng north-west of Hankow.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Ian Jack|title=Is this the end of Britishness|titleurl=http://www.theguardian.com/politics/commentisfree/2014/sep/16/-sp-is-this-the-end-of-britishness|journal=The Guardian|date=16 September 2014
|passage=Just upstream of Dryburgh Abbey, a reproduction of a classical Greek temple stands at the top of a wooded hillock on the riverâ€™s north '''bank'''.}}
# {{senseid|en|shoal such as sandbank}} {{lb|en|nautical|hydrology}} An [[elevation]] under the sea; a shallow area of shifting [[sand]], [[gravel]], [[mud]]{{,}} and so forth
#: {{syn|en|bar<id:shoal such as sandbank>}}
#: {{co|en|the '''banks''' of Newfoundland}}
# {{lb|en|geography}} A [[slope]] of earth, sand, etc.; an [[embankment]].
# {{lb|en|aviation}} The [[incline]] of an aircraft, especially during a turn.
# {{lb|en|rail}} An [[incline]], a [[hill]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1940|month=December|author=O. S. M. Raw|title=The Rhodesia Railways&mdash;II|journal=Railway Magazine|page=640|text=This is the hardest duty on the railway, for the trains are heavy and there are some long 1 in 40 '''banks'''.}}
# A [[mass]] of [[cloud]]s.
#: {{ux|en|The '''bank''' of clouds on the horizon announced the arrival of the predicted storm front.}}
# {{lb|en|mining}} The face of the coal at which miners are working.
# {{lb|en|mining}} A deposit of ore or coal, worked by excavations above water level.
# {{lb|en|mining}} The ground at the top of a shaft.
#: {{ux|en|Ores are brought to '''bank'''.}}

