{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|aviation}} To [[roll]] or [[incline]] laterally in order to [[turn]].
# {{senseid|en|to cause banking}} {{lb|en|transitive}} To cause (an aircraft) to '''bank'''.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To form into a bank or heap, to [[bank up]].
#: {{co|en|to '''bank''' sand}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of clouds}} To form a [[bank]]; to gather in masses.
#: {{syn|en|bank up}}
#* {{quote-book|en|date=2011-12-14|author=Sandra Birdsell|title=The Chrome Suite|publisher=Emblem Editions|isbn=9781551996851
|text={{...}} clouds '''banking''' above the gravel road, their flat slate-blue bottoms threatening freezing rain or an early snowfall.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To cover the embers of a fire with ashes in order to retain heat.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To raise a mound or dike about; to enclose, defend, or fortify with a bank; to [[embank]].
#* {{RQ:Pliny Holland Historie of the World
|passage=''Aristomaâˆ£chus'' would haue them to be stript from their leaues in winter, & in any hand to be '''banked''' well about, that the water stand not there in any hollow furrow or hole lower than the other ground}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To pass by the banks of.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=c. 1595|author=w:William Shakespeare| title={{w|King John (play)|King John}}| section=act 5, scene 2| passage=Have I not heard these islanders shout out / ''Vive le roi!'' as I have '''banked''' their towns?}}
# {{lb|en|rail|UK}} To provide additional power for a train ascending a bank (incline) by attaching another locomotive.
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1942|month=March|title=Notes and News: Locomotive Notes|journal=Railway Magazine|page=93|text=Some interesting facts have recently been made known by the L.N.E.R. concerning the 178-ton Garratt 2-8-0 + 0-8-2 engine No. 2395, which since construction in 1925 has spent the whole of its working life '''banking''' coal trains up the 3 miles of 1 in 40 between Wentworth junction and West Silkstone, on the Worsborough branch, near Barnsley.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=July|title=Motive Power Miscellany: Western Region|journal=Trains Illustrated|page=443|text=[...] the [[4-4-0]] unhappily stalled after a stop on Reading Old Bank with its eight-coach load and the Reading Up Line pilot, a "Hall", had to '''bank''' the train into Reading General.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1960|month=September|author=P. Ransome-Wallis|title=Modern motive power of the German Federal Railway: Part One|journal=Trains Ilustrated|page=558|text=Soon after leaving Bebra the line rises, mostly at 1 in 74, for 7 miles to Cornberg and all trains of over 400 tons are '''banked'''.}}

